  <static seed="1221" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/ComplexFractions/ComplexFractions1.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{\frac{x}{y}}}{{\frac{5x}{4y^{2}}}}=}</m><fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{4y}{5}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{\frac{x}{y}}}{{\frac{5x}{4y^{2}}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{\frac{x}{y}}</m> and <m>{\frac{5x}{4y^{2}}}</m>, which is <m>{4y^{2}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{\frac{x}{y}}}{{\frac{5x}{4y^{2}}}} \amp = \frac{{\frac{x}{y}}\cdot{4y^{2}}}{{\frac{5x}{4y^{2}}}\cdot{4y^{2}}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{4xy}}{{5x}} \amp  \\
    \amp = {\frac{4y}{5}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Note that you are not required to enter lost domain conditions in this problem, but it<rsq/>s good to know the following.</p>
<p>Since <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> were canceled, <m>x \ne 0</m> and <m>y \ne 0</m> are in the lost domain condition.</p>
</solution>
